  "bodyText": "DA\nEN\nREACH OUT\n\nSYSTEMS AND DEVELOPMENT\nBASED IN COPENHAGEN\n\nFORN IS A ONE-MAN ARMY SPECIALIZED IN\nsystems\nand\ndevelopment\nBASED IN COPENHAGEN,\n\nFEEDING OFF OF\n\ngrand\nambitions\n\nTO CREATE SOLUTIONS THAT CUT THROUGH THE NOISE.\n\nTHOUGHTS, RAMBLINGS AND VARIOUS\n\nstories\nDRAG\n\nThe new digital ID card from the Danish Agency for Digital Government is marketed as transparent, but in reality citizens are asked to hand over sensitive data blindly.\n\naltid and the debate on open source\nPRIVACY\n\nOn the fluid nature of human cooperation, the distance between work and the people who care about it, and why Balladic refuses to impose a shape.\n\nthe cooperation problem\nPRODUCT\n\nOn building a character-level transformer that cleans addresses - a two-million-parameter argument for specialization over scale.\n\nforty tokens\nMACHINE LEARNING\n\nOn the experience of working with Talos Linux across virtualized, bare metal and Hetzner environments - and what happens when the OS removes the premise of logging in.\n\nthe machine you can't log into\nPLATFORM ENGINEERING\n\nOn Svelte's compiler philosophy, SvelteKit's complex simplicity, and a small room in Stockholm where a community discovered it was real.\n\nthe framework that isn't there\nWEB DEVELOPMENT\n\nOn emergence, exotic computing substrates, and a grid of identical cells that learned to balance a pole through self-organization.\n\ngrowing computation\nMACHINE LEARNING\n\nOn the first thing I ever built - a consensus-based decision-making platform inspired by anarcho-syndicalist organizational models, hardcoded secrets and all.\n\nkonsent\nARCHITECTURE\n\nThe new digital ID card from the Danish Agency for Digital Government is marketed as transparent, but in reality citizens are asked to hand over sensitive data blindly.\n\naltid and the debate on open source\nPRIVACY\n\nOn the fluid nature of human cooperation, the distance between work and the people who care about it, and why Balladic refuses to impose a shape.\n\nthe cooperation problem\nPRODUCT\n\nOn building a character-level transformer that cleans addresses - a two-million-parameter argument for specialization over scale.\n\nforty tokens\nMACHINE LEARNING\n\nOn the experience of working with Talos Linux across virtualized, bare metal and Hetzner environments - and what happens when the OS removes the premise of logging in.\n\nthe machine you can't log into\nPLATFORM ENGINEERING\n\nOn Svelte's compiler philosophy, SvelteKit's complex simplicity, and a small room in Stockholm where a community discovered it was real.\n\nthe framework that isn't there\nWEB DEVELOPMENT\n\nOn emergence, exotic computing substrates, and a grid of identical cells that learned to balance a pole through self-organization.\n\ngrowing computation\nMACHINE LEARNING\n\nOn the first thing I ever built - a consensus-based decision-making platform inspired by anarcho-syndicalist organizational models, hardcoded secrets and all.\n\nkonsent\nARCHITECTURE\nCUSTOM INFRASTRUCTURE\nplatforms\n\nThere are (luckily) more options than Cloud or Chaos. I design and develop fundamentally digitally sovereign infrastructure that takes care of itself.\n\nREACH OUT\nSPECIALIZED NETWORKS\nmachine\nlearning\n\nGeneral models see general patterns, and waste enormous overhead on abilities that are never used. I work in the intersection of data, behavior and prediction, to help future teams solve old world problems with new world tools.\n\nREACH OUT\nCOMPLEX INTERACTIVITY\nweb apps\n\nWeb applications that do their job without making a fuss. From internal tooling to full platforms, with all the hard parts made invisible.\n\nREACH OUT\nSYSTEMS & DESIGN\narchitecture\n\nI build systems that shouldn't need me, and leverage experience from development, operations and business alike to create cohesion across professional boundaries.\n\nREACH OUT\n\nI EXCEL AT COMPLETELY\n\nsub\nmer\nging\n\nMYSELF IN A SINGLE GOAL, ALMOST DROWNING IN IT, AND EMERGING WITH A SOLUTION THAT FEELS COMPLETE.\n\nENOUGH OF ME; LET'S TALK ABOUT YOUR\n\nvision\n\nGET IN TOUCH YOUR WAY\nADRIAN@FORN.DK\n+45 28 68 81 40\n24 HOURS\nSIGNAL\nGITHUB\nLINKEDIN\nOR THE RIGHT WAY OR MY WAY\nSEND\n© FORN 2025\nCVR 39172569\nSYMBOLS FROM ASA'PILI BY P. M.\nCRAFTED WITH  +  BY\nADRIAN E. BRATLANN // FORN"
}